So I went to the British Museum in London with a 3D Scanner (3D Sense) and took scans of many famous ancient sculptures without permission till I was kicked out.

The sculpture originates from 1st-2nd Century BC Italy. Discovered in 1588, this ancient roman sculpture depicts the mythology of Ganymede and the Eagle.

I got in trouble for this so enjoy! As it's over 2000 years old and I scanned it without permission I'm releasing it under Public Domain. Do what you want with it! However attribution would be appreciated!

title: Battery shell for Keysight U5850 series thermal imager
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
A few of us have managed to snatch heavily discounted Keysight U5855A thermal imagers from a Keysight eBay clearance sale, but most of the units came completely bare.
Seeing as the battery sells for >$100 it became a bit of a challenge to find a homebrew solution.
See this thread for details and background:
http://www.eevblog.com/forum/thermal-imaging/keysight-u5855a-trueir-thermal-imager/

The case fits the 2x18650 cells and should have enough room to house a 2s BMS on top (important, since the camera drains the battery when off so if one forgets to remove it between uses it would cause a deep discharge).

I used tinned desoldering braid for the contacts. For the camera to charge the battery a 6.8k resistor is required between the Sense pin and positve, and a 10k one between the Temp pin and negative (originally a thermistor), see picture for polarity. I installed the resistors on the camera but added (untested) recesses to the case if someone wants to "do it right" and put them in the battery.

I used this BMS: https://fr.aliexpress.com/item/2S-4A-Li-ion-8-4V-18650-DIY-BMS-PCM-battery-protection-board-bms-pcm-for/32398042035.html?spm=2114.13010608.0.0.4vlzB6

title: Adoption module for Ants (To be used when an Ant Queen dies)

description.text:
THIS IS JUST MY EXPERIENCE, AND I WANT TO TELL IT TO YOU.
IF YOU TRY THIS, IT IS JUST AT YOUR OWN RISK.
ANYWAY, I HOPE THE ADOPTION WORKS FOR YOUR ANTS!

...BUT I MAINLY HOPE YOU DO NOT HAVE TO USE THIS MODULE.
I WISH YOU LUCK!!!

Hi, I'm very glad to present this design to you because I have a few ant colonies, and one mont ago I lost one of the Queens, so the rest of ants of that nest stayed without a "boss" or "mother".
The problem is that if you lose a queen, the ants die whith the time and no more new ants comes to the colony. So, in a few of time they all will be died :'(

I decided to do a test and try to make an adoption using another of my colonies.

After desing an adoption módule, I tested it and IT WORKED!! :D
They all are together and stay on peace now.

The adoption module consists in just a box with the appropiate shape to be connected to my other formicariums, and it also has an opening where we insert a special gate with a very fine metal mesh.

At the beginning of the experiment I had two colonies: One with a queen, and one without a queen.

I connected both colonies with the adoption module, and they stayed connected during two weeks, just having contact through the metal mesh. During this time they were sharing their smell.

After this adaptation period, to avoid too extress in the ants, I put the ants in the fridge (DO NOT USE THE FREEZER, they can die). After ten minutes they were very relaxed, with slow movements... It was the perfect moment to remove the gate that has the metal mesh, and insert a new gate with just a hole, without any mesh.

After a few of minutes, when the temperature reached an appropiate level, they explored the new rooms and became more active.

Now, when I'm writting this experience, they are very good.

Other info:
My ants are Messor barbarus, and they are very small colonies...I think they are less than fifty individuals.

To build the gate and install the metal mesh, you have to print two times the stl called "Lateral_rejillasV2.stl" and put inside (like a sandwich) the mesh. You have to stick it with glue. Then, there is another part, called "Holder.stl". You have to insert the "sandwich" in its opening, and stick it too with glue.

To get the mesh I used the filter of a water tap. If you use it, be sure that it is very thin. If not, the ants will pass across the mesh, and they are at risk.

I hope you understood my bad english.

title: Carriages for Anycubic Delta Kossel Linear Plus
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
UPDATE 30.06.17

Is anybody using any of these right now? Please comment if you do, share your opinion, share your makes! I'm currently working on an effector redesign on and off to make this more complete and get rid of the spacers entirely.

Original posting:

If you own an Anycubic Delta Kossel Linear Plus Printer that relies on these ugly workaround "copper spacers" that Anycubic ships to make up for their design mistakes - here's your solution to getting rid of half of them at least. :)

I took the original carriages ("belt tensioners" as Anycubic calls them) and redesigned them in Fusion 360.

Advantages:

  • Belt clearance improved. (No more friction on the left side of the carriages.)
  • Propper width makes "copper spacers" obsolete on the carriage side.
  • Improved stability/rigidity.

Disadvantages:

  • Due to the enhanced belt clearance, there are areas where less pressure might be applied to the GT6 belt as opposed to the original carriages (i.e. on the right side of the carriage). I tried to compensate for this by slightly slanting the surface from bottom to top (the original part does that too). Whether this is sufficient in the long run remains to be seen.

There are three versions: 50, 51 and 52mm wide. Each was designed for 2 M3x20mm screws, 2 M3 nuts (for the rods)+4 M3x8mm screws (linear rail slider) that originally shipped with the printer. THREE versions??? Well, here's why: Anycubic's "copper spacers" are somewhat too soft and flexible to give an exact spacing in the end. While the original effector's mounting screw distance is about 43mm, depending on the spacers you chose and the amount of force you applied on them during installation, you might end up with all kinds of diagonal rod mount distances at the effector in the end. In my case when using the "copper spacers" at the effector, I get distances of 50.8-51mm. (43mm+2x4.5mm=51mm.) YMMV! Since the rods in a delta have to be as closely parallel as possible, choose the spacing that suits your needs according to your measurements.

[The pictures above are from a pre-release 50mm version I'm using with 0.5mm spacers and custom made Traxxas 5347 ball joint rod ends and 250mm carbon rods for longer, more stable rods (total length 284mm) at the expense of z build height.]

description.text:
Update 5/3/2017
Removed Work in Progress. Its good to go.

Update 5/1/2017

M5 Nut traps were a bit sloppy. 1 out of 4 failed under load. footbase has much better fit and no slip under heavy tightening.

Yet Another Corner Design for the MPCNC 1" edition

I used these https://www.amazon.com/gp/product/B004TUEB4S/ref=oh_aui_detailpage_o02_s00?ie=UTF8&psc=1 SS tubes for my rails. I had 2 issues with the design.

1) I wanted to build it so I could change the work height to the job and still have a larger z for printing. The fit of the tubes to the legs was very tight and made it difficult to adjust the height easily.

2) I could not get a repeatable cross corner measurement which made it hard to square up. No solid surface to grab with the tape measure.

I looked at the top piece and it would be difficult to add a tab and keep the print orientation for no support printing.

I looked at the Totem stack. It had a couple issues. 1) no nut traps on the foot lock and 2) it changed the overall xy dimensions of the corner.

So I designed this thing:

All nuts have traps for easy tightening.
I used M5 and M3 socket head bolts (I had lots around from other projects), I like socket heads and despise phillips.
It has alignment tabs for checking that the base is perfectly square.

The Foot reuses the Base and has nut traps so I could bolt it to the table.
The foot is also shrunk down to the corner size (the original was slightly bigger) This allows the bolt holes to be set in another 1/8 of an inch or so from the edge of a minimal table size. Actually reduces min table size to rail length.

I have included the fusion 360 source. Most items are parameterized.

The included alignmenttop will work for equal length X and Y, if they are different you can change the top angle for cross corner measurements by setting the X and Y rail Length in the parameters and the angle will render at the correct angle. Just save the new part as stl.

You will need to print for 4 corners:

4 AlignmentTop.stl
2 Top.stl
2 TopM.stl
4 Spacer.stl (has 4 on the platter)
2 Middle.stl
2 MiddleM.stl
4 Bottom.stl
8 FootBase.stl

Will need the following Hardware:
16 M5x100 Socket Head Bolts
16 M5x(Table Thickness+10mm)
32 M5 Lock Nuts
8 M3x20 Socket Head Bolts
8 M3 Lock Nuts
8 Zipties
Optionally
32 M5 Washers

I have marked this as a work in progress. All fits have been tested but I have not finished building the machine. Will update once built.

This was a project I made with my daughter to teach her about 3d printing and 3d models.

How To Make Your Own

We used Fusion360 to build the model. One tip for beginners is that a couple of preference changes make Fusion360 easier to work with. Check "Z is up" and make your default units in mm.

Steps to design this project in Fusion360:
1) Add a canvas to the xy plane and import a picture of a flower onto it. I did a little resizing to get the scale we wanted the flower to be.
2) Add a sketch to the xy plane and use the line tool to reproduce one flower petal.
3) Add a circle for the middle of the flower
4) Use the 'circular pattern' sketch tool to repeat the petal around the middle
5) Draw the stem with the line tool
6) Extrude the petals, stem and center
7) Join all the 3d parts to a single part
8) Export stl and print using CURA

We printed this in pink PLA+ filament with default settings for PLA (CURA Wanhao edition) and it came out perfect.

description.text:
This is a great proof of the circle area formula with no calculus necessary.

The circular dish holds 10 equal wedges. The parallelogram rearranges the wedges into an orientation that is starting to look rectangular.

The point of the lab is for the kids to see that if you divide the circle into enough wedges, you can arrange them into a rectangle whose height is equal to the radius of the circle, and whose width is equal to pi x radius (half the circumference). From the rectangle area formula, we can then see that the area of a circle is pi times radius^2.

I made one of these for my kids. For a real math lesson, it would be nice to have 3-4 different versions with the same size circle broken into 4, 10, 20 pieces. That would make it clear that with enough pieces, the wedges can be arranged into a rectangle. You could also print wedges on card stock and have the kids cut it out so you don't have to print all the wedges.

The pieces were a tight fit in my templates, but fit well once I sanded the rough spots off the edges. Templates are optional.

Circle area formula is pi times radius squared.
This demonstration shows that you can cut a circle into wedges, and arrange those wedges into an approximately rectangular shape.
Assuming the kids have already been taught the concepts of radius, circumference, and the rectangle area formula, they should be able to follow this proof and 'discover' the circle area formula.
This demonstration also hints at concepts of limits and infinity, but does not really require understanding of them.

Hopefully this is enough detail... Materials to be prepared ahead:
One set of 10 printed wedges per group. Round and parallelogram trays are optional, but one of each per group is needed if you use them. alternative materials:
One print of a circle divided evenly into about 10 wedges plus two pairs of scissors per group. The circle can be cut in half so two people can cut wedges. Arrange the wedges into a circle. Talk about the property of area. Review concepts of radius and circumference. Have kids arrange wedges in alternate pattern... 1 pointing up, 1 pointing down, etc. The final arrangement should look roughly like a parallelogram except that the sides will be bumpy. Talk to them about it looking rectangular, and if it were rectangular, what would the dimensions be? And what would the area be? Discuss the idea of using smaller wedges. If you had enough wedges, would the rectangular become more perfect? The goals of this lesson are (1) teach the circle area formula (2) hands on discovery that most kids should enjoy (3) introduction to the idea of a proving or deriving a math concept and (4) introduction to the idea of a limit.

description.text:
I designed this very simple clip to work with the metal spool holder bracket that came with my FlyingBear P902 printer, but it is possible that others with a printer with a 2020 aluminum strut frame may find it useful as well. Before I designed and installed this clip, I would sometimes lose prints because the filament spool would drift on the spool bracket, and the filament would get tangled on the spool bracket. This clip solved that problem. Not only did it hold the spool in place so that it would not drift on the spool bracket, but it also prevented filament from getting caught on the bracket behind the spool.

I don't use this clip anymore, since I later found that spools with small diameter center holes would not turn very well on the metal spool bracket, and I have since upgraded to my ball-bearing spool holder design. (This can be found at http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2211078). However, I thought that I would post this clip because it is very simple, and perhaps others might find it useful.

https://www.banggood.com/Eachine-Aurora-68-68mm-Mini-5_8G-600TVL-FPV-Racing-Drone-BNF-with-F3-OSD-48CH-25mW-VTX-p-1132680.html?rmmds=search

I decided to start this project because stock frame is very fragile - in lightest crash camera tower pops out, duct brakes and so on.

Copter weight increased only 3.7gr after the mod. But the frame is much stronger than the stock cabon. Weight increase is due to the M2 screws I used for the frame and motors also.
M2 gives better joints and allows use softmonts for the the motors (stock screwsare cone). I STRONGLY RECOMEND SOFTMOUNTS like these http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2211030
otherwise no matter stock or moded copter with float or vibrate. Softmounts is a MUST for microcopters.

There are several versios for usage with stocks screws or M2 and with or without softmounts. Stock/M2 has screw shaft difference by 0.2mm, soft/nosoft has difference in ducts hight position - difference by 1.5mm as softmounts lifts motors and protection should be lifted also.

Everything can be printed in:
-PLA or ePA-CF (nylon-carbon that i recommend)
-0.4 nozzle, 0.15 layer
-100% infill, supports on.
Printer should be very precise. I use Creality 3D CR-8 from banggood.

This is a case for the Iphone 7 plus. This case is split into two halves that allows it to be printed on smaller printers and using non-flexible filament like PLA. The original design was made by zlagger.

If you make your shell thickness very thin, then you can choose your case design by choosing the infill pattern.

This version may have to be slightly trimmed on the snap in pieces because of printer inconsistency.

For the Take Your Child To Work Day this year myself and a friend decided that we would do a marble run for the children. Rather than ordering tracks and pieces to assemble them with, we decided to create/print our own tracks. We created them in a way that the children could use Legos to hold the tracks. We also created a slanted Lego piece to assist in angling the tracks.

You should not use supports for the slanted lego pieces. If you do they may be hard to use

You can read about the marble run here: http://3ddash.blogspot.com/2017/04/marble-run.html

What is a marble run If you do not know what a marble run is; it is where you have multiple teams that need to assemble tracks together that a marble can roll down and whichever team uses the most tracks or, as a tie breaker, has the fastest run wins. The catch is if the tracks are too steep, and the marble has too much speed, the marble will jump the track and the team will be disqualified.
We assembled the children into teams of four and gave them 35 minutes to see how what they could come up with.

Some straight and curved tracks (print them)

description.text:
EDIT: Added a real life photo of them (quick and dirty print), and the directions below.

I recently got myself a brand new Wanaho Duplicator i3 PLUS, and was looking around the web for things to do with it... that's when I found it:

The dreaded RECALL!

It seems that the springs between the heated bed and its support will rub the insulator off the board, which in turn can cause a short, or other nastiness.

You really only need four to fix the problem, but why not install 8 (one on the top and bottom of each spring), to keep your springs straight up and down? 9 are included on this STL just in case one doesn't print correctly.

Safety first, all!

Directions:

  1. Print this .stl
  2. After your bed has cooled, power off, unplug, and remove all cables from the printer.
  3. Grab a T8 scredriver and a pair of pliers.
  4. Completely remove the thumbscrews from the bottom of the mounting plate.
  5. Lift the heated bed off the mounting plate, being careful not to damage the wires connected between the mounting plate and the heated bed.
  6. Remove the springs and set them in a safe place.
  7. Use the pliers to hold the nut (if there is one) which is underneath the heated bed. Use the T8 screwdriver to unscrew the screw and remove the nut.
  8. Slide one of the guides you just printed onto the screw, then replace the nut you just took off. If there was an insulating washer there, it's your choice to leave it or remove it (I removed mine.) Make sure the nut is nice and snug.
  9. Replace the spring and put another guide on the bottom of it.
  10. Do the same thing to the other three corners.
  11. Replace the thumbscrews.
  12. Re-level your bed. (I usually do this twice to three times to get it just perfect.)
  13. ...
  14. PROFIT!

Spent way too much time on this but here it is. its a truly self inking stamp. You will need a spring and sponge to complete the project. Try to print every thing upside down and use supports as required, I only needed supports for the round bits to make it as smooth as possible. Every thing else has been designed to print without supports.

Instructions:

  1. sand round parts if needed, smooth on all the round parts is key!.
  2. Glue the sponge (2.5mm thick for regular size up to 1/2" for a the tall version) into the inside ceiling of the base.

In fact, be sure to line it up right, because it doesn't rotate or come off easily. Also, be careful not to bend or stretch it too much, as it can develop cracks that could weaken it.
Used on 4 icons for a 10 day trip to WDW, with no issues, including an extra one that I had cut in two with a dremel (wanted to see if I could safely drill a hole for a lanyard - FYI: no, you can't), where the keeper was the only thing holding the two halves together!

description.text:

I weigh about 200 lbs. and was swinging around a bit so a couple extra lbs. of centrifugal force too. Tied to 3mm Kevlar line. Don't actually use this for anything life threatening, obviously.

Printed with PLA 100% infill, a raft is a must because it warps so much while printing. The two piece file is included if anyone wants to improve on it, it broke at the slot so a larger hook with more material around that area may help, but the goal was to make a weight bearing grappling hook that was as small as possible.
